The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, July 9: A businessman was stabbed to death in front of his wife allegedly by four unidentified men at their west Delhi residence today after he refused to give them Rs 4 lakh, reports our correspondent.          
	Police said 32-year-old Jagmohan Singh Kohlis wife Sumit was the prime suspect. She had returned to Kholis house yesterday after living apart for four months.           
	The police said there were loopholes in her statement. Sumit said the men trussed her up but she managed to free herself and inform the police. But the cops said they found no sign of forced entry in the house.           
	Kohlis relatives alleged Sumit had left the house following problems with her husband over his property. They accused her of being behind the murder.                   
	 Washington (PTI): Fast food restaurant chain Burger King has apologised for running an advertisement involving goddess Lakshmi in Spain that allegedly offended Hindus. The Hindu American Foundation said on Wednesday that Burger King was running a print ad that depicted Lakshmi sitting on a meat sandwich and other foodstuff. The ad has been removed.                  
	 Hyderabad (PTI): Police arrested a youth from Uttar Pradesh who tried to enter Sania Mirzas Hyderabad house on Thursday saying he had got a love letter from the tennis player. On Wednesday, a man from Bangalore was arrested for barging into Sanias house and saying he wanted to marry her.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court on Thursday rejected the plea for a CBI inquiry into alleged illegal burial of 22 people killed in the 2002 post-Godhra violence. The court said the petitioners, family members of one of the victims from a minority community, had approached the court after seven years of the alleged burial.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The government has appointed K. Kasturirangan, the former chairman of Indian Space Research Organisation, as a member of the Planning Commission.                                                                                                                           
